segments.text: Yes, I have it, but I don't remember.
Yes, and what year did you come to the United States?
Well, here in this place we came in 1921, about half a year ago, as they say, to speak Spanish.
Well, tell me a little about your mother and father.
Yes, she was a very, very kind woman with a very, very big heart, with a lot of friendship and love for everyone.
She was a very charming person.
And how many children did she have?
How many children did Micaela have?
And you lived in Monterrey during these last years?
My parents came here, near Rio Grande, to the other side of Mexico.
Well, in Nuevo León, but in Tamaulipas, where we came from.
I came here to live there.
I don't know anything about Tamaulipas.
I was born there, but I don't know anything.
My parents came here to live in the river, to use the word.
Y todos nacieron en México, los hermanos, ¿verdad?
¿Y qué clase de trabajo tenía su papá?
Él trabajaba en la agricultura, en la labor.
¿Contieres de suyo o de otra persona?
Well, she went to the center.
Do you want a cup of coffee?
Oh, do you already have coffee?
Yes, I don't have it right now, it's for you.
I'll just have a little drink, it's a lot.
Put it on the table, please.
Well, tell me, perhaps, please, a few things about your childhood.
I didn't go to school because it hurt me.
I lost an eye since I was a baby.
It hasn't been long since I lost it here on this ranch.
What's the name of that ranch?
No, no, in Mexico, in Nuevo León.
Oh, it didn't have a name, Rancho Chiquito.
I mean, it didn't have a name.
The village was close to the town.
There was a little house there.
But it wasn't a big ranch that had names.
But it was close to what town?
It was a town called General Treviño.
It was close to this town.
And did you also work with your father?
I was very young at that time.
Did his father die there in Monterrey?
He died there because he went to purify himself there and his people stayed there, where he was from.
They lived here in the town of Treviño.
He got very sick and went to purify himself there.
And he never came to the United States.
He never came to the United States.
Robestown had some relatives, daughters of a sister of mine.
She got a little sick and she took her father to the hospital.
After her father died, what does her mother do with five children?
She works in the houses with the ladies.
They had a little bit of money, they gave them a little bit of work, they gave them a little bit of money.
And in the ranch, or where?
And then, in what year did your family come here to Texas?
For what reason did you come to your family to Texas?
To work a little to earn some food.
Was the work better here or not?
There is more work here than...
In what way do you understand that there is good work here?
Well, wasn't it for the reason of the revolution?
In these years there is a revolution, right?
I remember it was already a little big.
When there was a lot of revolution in Mexico in those years.
Tell me about the revolution, please.
No, I can't tell you because I was very young.
It didn't stay in my mind.
Yes, but what does your mother say about these things?
I can't tell you what she said.
¿Hay soldados o otras cosas como esto?
Venían soldados así nomás, eran pueblos chiquitos, nomás andaban así en los pueblos ellos.
Venían de los pueblos grandes de México.
When you came to the United States, what kind of work was there for your mother?
Here in Robstown or somewhere else?
Here in this place, because we've been here all the time since we came from Mexico.
And did you visit Mexico after you left?
Do you know Mexico in these past years?
When I was there, I didn't want to go back.
When we came here, I didn't want to go back.
The two siblings of a man have already died.
I have two sisters, two sisters are women.
One lives in Lobos and the other lives in Austin.
Well, when you lived in Mexico, what kind of house did you have?
Tell me about your house in Mexico.
to the poor, not a good big house.
And it was made of what kind of material?
Material, a material that in Mexico is that they take out of the sky some stones that they call, what do they call it?
Yes, some blocks that they take out, they compose them.
They take them out of the land and put them in houses.
They liked to come back here, to this side.
And what do you pay in Mexico?
A lot of money or little?
In those days they paid a little.
And when you came here to the United States, how did you come?
By car or by train or what?
Tell me a little about the trip.
Tell me the story of this trip.
No, I don't have much to talk about.
I don't have much to talk about.
Because I don't have much on my mind.
I don't have much to talk about.
The weather is very rainy, yes.
It looks like it's going to rain all day, who knows.
But now, it rained a lot for about three weeks.
And you lived here for almost your whole life?
You don't look at anything anymore?
